ce:section.ce:para:
The preparation of CDs and CDs-MIPs was illustrated in Scheme 1
                        . As shown in Scheme 1A, hydroxyl, carboxyl and nitro groups functionalized CDs with blue fluorescence property were synthesized via a microwave reaction. The quantum yield (QY) of the CDs was evaluated to reach 16.2% with quinine sulfate as standard. Meanwhile, the influences of UV irradiation and NaCl concentration as well as pH on the fluorescence intensity of the CDs were assessed in order to examine the inherent stability of carbon dots derived from orange peels (Fig. 1
                        ). As depicted in Fig. 1A, CDs solution was under continuous irradiation with a beam of UV light at 360 nm for 60 min and the FL intensity underwent a slight change, indicating a stable photostability. Similarly, the CDs was also stabilized when using various concentrations of NaCl, up to the concentration of 800 mM, as experiment condition (Fig. 1B). In addition, the fluorescence intensity under different pH in range of 2 to 12 was studied. As shown in Fig. 1C, the fluorescence intensity was steady ranging from 2 to 9, but obviously decreased at pH = 10–12. The result indicated that the biomass CDs had a wide range of pH adjustment but unstable to alkaline environment.
